The United States is revising its annual refugee admissions cap to 62,500 for this fiscal year, erasing the historically low number set by the previous administration of 15,000. This change reflects America's values as a nation that welcomes and supports refugees. The new admissions cap will also support efforts to expand the country's capacity to admit refugees, with a goal of reaching 125,000 refugee admissions in the coming fiscal year. The aim is to remove any doubt in the minds of refugees worldwide who have suffered and are eagerly awaiting their new lives. The United States Refugee Admissions Program represents America's commitment to protect the most vulnerable and serve as a beacon of liberty and refuge. The administration intends to rebuild and expedite the screening process for refugees already in the pipeline for admission. While it may take time to achieve the 62,500 admissions this year, efforts are already underway to undo the damage of the previous four years. The program has been reopened to new refugees, and changes to regional allocations have increased the number of refugees ready for departure to the United States. The budget submitted to Congress reflects the administration's commitment to the goal of 125,000 refugee admissions in the first fiscal year. Achieving this goal may be challenging, but the administration will utilize every available tool to assist fully-vetted refugees fleeing dire conditions in their home countries. This action aims to reaffirm American leadership and values in refugee admissions.